Famous 1970s discotheques included "...cocaine-filled  hangouts such as 's '''' ", which  was operated by  and . Studio 54 was notorious for the hedonism that went on within; the balconies were known for sexual encounters, and drug use was rampant. Its dance floor was decorated with an image of the "Man in the Moon" that included an animated cocaine spoon. Other famous discotheques included the ''Loft'', the ''Paradise Garage'', and ''Aux Puces'', one of the first gay disco bars.
Today the term discothèque is usually synonymous with s in  because disco music is still very popular there, but in contemporary English usage it is now very dated<ref>{{cite web | last = | first =
  | title =Definition of Discotheque - Cambridge Advanced Learners Dictionary | publisher = | url =http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=22184&dict=CALD | accessdate =2007-22-01 }}</ref>, because nightclubs have not been commonly called "discos" since the early 1980s. The term "" was originally a 1960s US abbreviation of ''discothèque'', a place where "disco music" was played.
The term , which is a shortened form of discothèque, refers to a specific style of  that was derived in U.S.A. from  and , and to the  styles popular in 1970s disco clubs (e.g., "The Hustle"). In Europe the same term used for the European Disco productions, that had 50s and 60s Europop influences. Later, those European productions (mostly Italian and German) were named "" and "Disco" was only used for the U.S.A. productions.
